If \u003ccode\u003emergeStaticsConfig=true\u003c/code\u003e, this value will be merged with your webpack's \u003ccode\u003eoutput.path: publicPath\u003c/code\u003e for stripping prefixes. Otherwise this property will be passed directly to \u003ccode\u003esw-precache\u003c/code\u003e and webpack's output path won't be replaced.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eNote that all configuration options are optional. \u003ccode\u003eSWPrecacheWebpackPlugin\u003c/code\u003e will by default use all your assets emitted by webpack's compiler for the \u003ccode\u003estaticFileGlobs\u003c/code\u003e parameter and your webpack config's \u003ccode\u003e{[output.path + '/']: output.publicPath}\u003c/code\u003e as the \u003ccode\u003estripPrefixMulti\u003c/code\u003e parameter. This behavior is probably what you want, all your webpack assets will be cached by your generated service worker. configuration options to <code>SWPrecacheWebpackPlugin</code>:</p><p dir="auto"><strong>plugin options</strong>:</p><ul dir="auto"><li><code>filename</code>: <code>[String]</code> - Service worker filename, default is <code>service-worker.js</code></li><li><code>filepath</code>: <code>[String]</code> - Service worker path and name, default is to use <code>webpack.output.path</code> + <code>options.filename</code>. This will override <code>filename</code>. <em>Warning: Make the service worker available in the same directory it will be needed. This is because the scope of the service worker is defined by the directory the worker exists.</em></li><li><code>staticFileGlobsIgnorePatterns</code>: <code>[RegExp]</code> - Define an optional array of regex patterns to filter out of staticFileGlobs (see below)</li><li><code>mergeStaticsConfig</code>: <code>[boolean]</code> - Merge provided staticFileGlobs and stripPrefixMulti with webpack's config, rather than having those take precedence, default is false.</li><li><code>minify</code>: <code>[boolean]</code> - Set to true to minify and uglify the generated service-worker, default is false.</li></ul><p dir="auto"><a href="https://github.com/GoogleChrome/sw-precache#options-parameter" title="SW-Precache Options"><strong><code>sw-precache</code> options</strong></a>:Pass any option from <code>sw-precache</code> into your configuration. Some of these will be automatically be populated if you do not specify the value and a couple others will be modified to be more compatible with webpack. Options that are populated / modified:</p><ul dir="auto"><li><code>cacheId</code>: <code>[String]</code> - Not required but you should include this, it will give your service worker cache a unique name. Defaults to "sw-precache-webpack-plugin".</li><li><code>importScripts</code>: <code>[Array<String|Object>]</code><ul dir="auto"><li>When importScripts array item is a <code>String</code>:<ul dir="auto"><li>Converts to object format <code>{ filename: '<publicPath>/my-script.js'}</code></li></ul></li><li>When importScripts array item is an <code>Object</code>:<ul dir="auto"><li>Looks for <code>chunkName</code> property.</li><li>Looks for <code>filename</code> property.</li><li><strong>If a <code>chunkName</code> is specified, it will override the accompanied value for <code>filename</code>.</strong></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><code>replacePrefix</code>: <code>[String]</code> - Should only be used in conjunction with <code>stripPrefix</code></li><li><code>runtimeCaching</code>: <code>[Array<Object>]</code> - Configures runtime caching for dynamic content such as HTTP requests. Refer to <a href="https://github.com/GoogleChromeLabs/sw-precache#runtimecaching-arrayobject">sw-precache </a> to see all available options.</li><li><code>staticFileGlobs</code>: <code>[Array<String>]</code> - Omit this to allow the plugin to cache all your bundles' emitted assets. If <code>mergeStaticsConfig=true</code>: this value will be merged with your bundles' emitted assets, otherwise this value is just passed to <code>sw-precache</code> and emitted assets won't be included.</li><li><code>stripPrefix</code>: <code>[String]</code> - Same as <code>stripPrefixMulti[stripPrefix] = ''</code></li><li><code>stripPrefixMulti</code>: <code>[Object<String,String>]</code> - Omit this to use your webpack config's <code>output.path + '/': output.publicPath</code>. If <code>mergeStaticsConfig=true</code>, this value will be merged with your webpack's <code>output.path: publicPath</code> for stripping prefixes. Otherwise this property will be passed directly to <code>sw-precache</code> and webpack's output path won't be replaced.</li></ul><p dir="auto"><em>Note that all configuration options are optional. <code>SWPrecacheWebpackPlugin</code> will by default use all your assets emitted by webpack's compiler for the <code>staticFileGlobs</code> parameter and your webpack config's <code>{[output.path + '/']: output.publicPath}</code> as the <code>stripPrefixMulti</code> parameter. This behavior is probably what you want, all your webpack assets will be cached by your generated service worker. Just don't pass any arguments when you initialize this plugin, and let this plugin handle generating your <code>sw-precache</code> configuration.</em></p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 If you wish to test the service worker locally, you can use simple a node server <a href="/goldhand/sw-precache-webpack-plugin/blob/master/examples">see example project</a> or <code>python SimpleHTTPServer</code> from your build directory. I would suggest pointing your node server to a different port than your usual local development port and keeping the precache service worker out of your <a href="https://github.com/goldhand/cookiecutter-webpack/blob/986151474b60dc19166eba18156a1f9dbceecb98/%7B%7Bcookiecutter.repo_name%7D%7D/webpack.local.config.js" title="webpack local config example">local configuration (example)</a>.</p><p dir="auto">Or add <code>setup</code> section to <code>devServer</code> config, e.g.:</p><div class="snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="module.exports = {    devServer: {        setup: function (app) {            app.get('/service-worker.js', function (req, res) {                res.set({ 'Content-Type': 'application/javascript; charset=utf-8' });                res.send(fs.readFileSync('build/service-worker.js'));            });        }    }}"><pre class="notranslate"><code>module.exports = {    devServer: {        setup: function (app) {            app.get('/service-worker.js', function (req, res) {                res.set({ 'Content-Type': 'application/javascript; charset=utf-8' });                res.send(fs.readFileSync('build/service-worker.js'));            });        }    }}</code></pre></div><p dir="auto">There will likely never be <code>webpack-dev-server</code> support. <code>sw-precache</code> needs physical files in order to generate the service worker. <code>webpack-dev-server</code> files are in-memory. It is only possible to provide <code>sw-precache</code> with globs to find these files. It will follow the glob pattern and generate a list of file names to cache.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Contributing</h2><a
